-----------------------------------------------------------------

Welcome back to The Daily Courant, your afternoon guide to Puck=E2=80=99s b=
est new reporting.

=C2=A0

First up today, Dylan Byers returns to the scene of the crime at The Washin=
gton Post, where a fresh wave of departures and defections risks obscuring =
the deeper, more complex reality of Jeff Bezos=E2=80=99s growing influence =
over the paper. Everyone from Marty Baron to Ruth Marcus seems to have an o=
pinion on the Post=E2=80=99s center-right
slide. But as Dylan argues, is Bezos=E2=80=99s decision to refashion the Op=
inion section actually a capitulation to Trump, or merely a realignment wit=
h a longstanding journalistic tradition?

=C2=A0

Plus, below the fold: Leigh Ann Caldwell gets inside the heads of Senate De=
mocrats as Chuck Schumer struggles to articulate the party=E2=80=99s next b=
udget moves.
Bill Cohan heralds the age of media lawfare on Wall Street. Rachel Strugatz=
 evaluates LVMH=E2=80=99s surprising bet on Pat McGrath. And exclusively fo=
r Inner Circle members, Marion Maneker makes sense of the nebulous results =
from London=E2=80=99s latest art auctions.

=C2=A0

Meanwhile, on the pods: Matt Belloni invites high-powered entertainment
lawyer Bryan Freedman on The Town to vamp on the state of play in the ongoi=
ng Baldoni vs. Lively saga. And on The Powers That Be, Abby Livingston join=
s Peter Hamby to discuss whether Democrats will cross the aisle to support =
the G.O.P.=E2=80=99s budget resolution to stave off a government shutdown.

